content.text:
Price: Falafel wrap £5.50; three plain naan £1.50.

【52†Read more】

【53†Sonora】

【53†8. Sonora Taquería】

  * Restaurants 
  * Mexican 
  * Stoke Newington 
  * price 1 of 4

A slice of Echo Park in Stoke Newington, this LA-style taco joint offers a short menu of grill and guisado (braised) tacos. Most are pork and beef-based, though there’s a cactus leaf nopales offering for vegetarians and faux chorizo for vegans. A sensible diner would order three tacos, but you’d be within your rights to order four, even five. Prices are an extremely reasonable £3.50 to £5, and though they look petite, Sonora’s paper-thin tortillas come packed to the floury brim. Truly excellent stuff. 

Price: Carne asada taco; £4.50, barbacoa taco £4; bean quesadilla £2.

[Image 4: https://media.timeout.com/images/106138839/image.jpg]

【37†Leonie Cooper】 Food and Drink Editor, Time Out London

【53†Read more】

Advertising

【54†Leonie Cooper for Time Out】

【54†9. Kowloon Bakery】

  * Restaurants 
  * Chinese 
  * Chinatown 

Bargain Cantonese bakes line the windows of this Chinatown mainstay. Swerve the buffet and instead focus on the bakery where you can score a crispy BBQ pork bun for £2 and onion buns for an even more reasonable £1.50. Sweets comes cheap too, with crispy coconut buns at £1.50 and chocolate tiger rolls and pandan swiss rolls for £1.80. 

Price: Crispy BBQ pork bun £2.

[Image 5: https://media.timeout.com/images/106138839/image.jpg]

【37†Leonie Cooper】 Food and Drink Editor, Time Out London

【54†Read more】

【55†Laura Gallant for Time Out】

【55†10. Toconoco】

  * Restaurants 
  * Japanese 
  * Haggerston 
  * price 1 of 4 

This kid-friendly Japanese café canalside on the Kingsland Basin, close to Haggerston station, offers up an ever-changing daily set lunch menu of a main dish, rice, miso soup and a small salad. Always delicious and always packed full of variety, there are also rice balls, teas, Japanese toasts and desserts. The name translates as 'kids on the floor', so expect a few of those, too. 

Price: Set lunch £8.40

【55†Read more】

Advertising

【56†Bryan Mayes for Time Out】

【56†11. Oyster Shack & Seafood Bar】

  * Restaurants 
  * Seafood 
  * Essex 
  * price 1 of 4 

Get on your bike (quite literally, as it's near the bikers paradise that is the High Beech tea hut) and head down to this seriously fresh seafood spot in the heart of Epping Forest. Open Thursday to Sunday, swing by for hot and cold platters full of prawns, cockles, whelks and more. 

Price: Pint of cold prawns; £6.50

【56†Read more】

【57†Caitlin Isola】

【57†12. Mystic Burek】

  * Restaurants 
  * Balkan 
  * Sydenham 
  * price 1 of 4 

Spasia Dinkovski whips up traditional Macedonian filo pies using her grandma’s recipes; semi-psychedelic swirls of pastry packed with ground meat, gooey cheese, and enough butter to make you see into the future. Find them at her Sydenham cafe – a former Italian deli – where the short menu lists four bureks and one sweet and sour cherry baklava bun. Scoff your hearty slice surrounded by accoutrements of Balkan culture and to a Northern Soul soundtrack. Heaven.

Price: Burek slices from £7. Cup of tea; £1. 

[Image 6: https://media.timeout.com/images/106138839/image.jpg]

【37†Leonie Cooper】 Food and Drink Editor, Time Out London

【57†Read more】

Advertising

【58†Andy Parsons for Time Out】

【58†13. M Manze】

  * Restaurants 
  * Pie and mash shop 
  * Bermondsey 

Michele Manze and family arrived from Italy in 1878, started out as ice-cream merchants and finally opened this pie, mash and eel shop on Tower Bridge Road in 1902. Inside, little seems to have changed since those early days: the Victorian green-tiled interiors speak of history, while the pie and mash is reckoned to be some of the best in town. A truly iconic London feast and one that comes with a reasonable price to boot. 

Price: Pie and mash, £5.50.

【58†Read more】

【59†Southampton Arms】

【59†14. Southampton Arms】

  * Bars and pubs 
  * Pubs 
  * Gospel Oak 
  * price 2 of 4 

The sign outside announces ‘ale, cider, meat’, and that pretty much sums up what’s on offer at one of the best pubs in north London. It's their small but powerful

Here are some great options for a cheap lunch near you:

1. **Pizza Union** - Known for their affordable thin-crust pizzas with various toppings, Pizza Union offers a budget-friendly and delicious meal in a trendy setting【6†source】.
2. **Sonora Taquería** - This LA-style taco joint offers a variety of tacos priced between £3.50 to £5, with both meat and vegetarian options【7†source】.
3. **Kowloon Bakery** - Located in Chinatown, this bakery offers a variety of cheap eats like crispy BBQ pork buns for £2 and other baked goods starting from £1.50【7†source】.
4. **Mystic Burek** - Serving traditional Macedonian filo pies, this cafe offers hearty slices from £7 in a culturally rich atmosphere【7†source】.

These spots provide a mix of international flavors at reasonable prices, making them excellent choices for an inexpensive lunch.

metadata.text:
Price: Falafel wrap £5.50; three plain naan £1.50.

【52†Read more】

【53†Sonora】

【53†8. Sonora Taquería】

  * Restaurants 
  * Mexican 
  * Stoke Newington 
  * price 1 of 4

A slice of Echo Park in Stoke Newington, this LA-style taco joint offers a short menu of grill and guisado (braised) tacos. Most are pork and beef-based, though there’s a cactus leaf nopales offering for vegetarians and faux chorizo for vegans. A sensible diner would order three tacos, but you’d be within your rights to order four, even five. Prices are an extremely reasonable £3.50 to £5, and though they look petite, Sonora’s paper-thin tortillas come packed to the floury brim. Truly excellent stuff. 

Price: Carne asada taco; £4.50, barbacoa taco £4; bean quesadilla £2.

[Image 4: https://media.timeout.com/images/106138839/image.jpg]

【37†Leonie Cooper】 Food and Drink Editor, Time Out London

【53†Read more】

Advertising

【54†Leonie Cooper for Time Out】

【54†9. Kowloon Bakery】

  * Restaurants 
  * Chinese 
  * Chinatown 

Bargain Cantonese bakes line the windows of this Chinatown mainstay. Swerve the buffet and instead focus on the bakery where you can score a crispy BBQ pork bun for £2 and onion buns for an even more reasonable £1.50. Sweets comes cheap too, with crispy coconut buns at £1.50 and chocolate tiger rolls and pandan swiss rolls for £1.80. 

Price: Crispy BBQ pork bun £2.

[Image 5: https://media.timeout.com/images/106138839/image.jpg]

【37†Leonie Cooper】 Food and Drink Editor, Time Out London

【54†Read more】

【55†Laura Gallant for Time Out】

【55†10. Toconoco】

  * Restaurants 
  * Japanese 
  * Haggerston 
  * price 1 of 4 

This kid-friendly Japanese café canalside on the Kingsland Basin, close to Haggerston station, offers up an ever-changing daily set lunch menu of a main dish, rice, miso soup and a small salad. Always delicious and always packed full of variety, there are also rice balls, teas, Japanese toasts and desserts. The name translates as 'kids on the floor', so expect a few of those, too. 

Price: Set lunch £8.40

【55†Read more】

Advertising

【56†Bryan Mayes for Time Out】

【56†11. Oyster Shack & Seafood Bar】

  * Restaurants 
  * Seafood 
  * Essex 
  * price 1 of 4 

Get on your bike (quite literally, as it's near the bikers paradise that is the High Beech tea hut) and head down to this seriously fresh seafood spot in the heart of Epping Forest. Open Thursday to Sunday, swing by for hot and cold platters full of prawns, cockles, whelks and more. 

Price: Pint of cold prawns; £6.50

【56†Read more】

【57†Caitlin Isola】

【57†12. Mystic Burek】

  * Restaurants 
  * Balkan 
  * Sydenham 
  * price 1 of 4 

Spasia Dinkovski whips up traditional Macedonian filo pies using her grandma’s recipes; semi-psychedelic swirls of pastry packed with ground meat, gooey cheese, and enough butter to make you see into the future. Find them at her Sydenham cafe – a former Italian deli – where the short menu lists four bureks and one sweet and sour cherry baklava bun. Scoff your hearty slice surrounded by accoutrements of Balkan culture and to a Northern Soul soundtrack. Heaven.

Price: Burek slices from £7. Cup of tea; £1. 

[Image 6: https://media.timeout.com/images/106138839/image.jpg]

【37†Leonie Cooper】 Food and Drink Editor, Time Out London

【57†Read more】

Advertising

【58†Andy Parsons for Time Out】

【58†13. M Manze】

  * Restaurants

This kid-friendly Japanese café canalside on the Kingsland Basin, close to Haggerston station, offers up an ever-changing daily set lunch menu of a main dish, rice, miso soup and a small salad. Always delicious and always packed full of variety, there are also rice balls, teas, Japanese toasts and desserts. The name translates as 'kids on the floor', so expect a few of those, too. 

Price: Set lunch £8.40

【55†Read more】

【56†Bryan Mayes for Time Out】

【56†11. Oyster Shack & Seafood Bar】

  * Restaurants 
  * Seafood 
  * Essex 
  * price 1 of 4 

Get on your bike (quite literally, as it's near the bikers paradise that is the High Beech tea hut) and head down to this seriously fresh seafood spot in the heart of Epping Forest. Open Thursday to Sunday, swing by for hot and cold platters full of prawns, cockles, whelks and more. 

Price: Pint of cold prawns; £6.50

【56†Read more】

【57†Caitlin Isola】

【57†12. Mystic Burek】

  * Restaurants 
  * Balkan 
  * Sydenham 
  * price 1 of 4 

Spasia Dinkovski whips up traditional Macedonian filo pies using her grandma’s recipes; semi-psychedelic swirls of pastry packed with ground meat, gooey cheese, and enough butter to make you see into the future. Find them at her Sydenham cafe – a former Italian deli – where the short menu lists four bureks and one sweet and sour cherry baklava bun. Scoff your hearty slice surrounded by accoutrements of Balkan culture and to a Northern Soul soundtrack. Heaven.

Price: Burek slices from £7. Cup of tea; £1. 

[Image 6: https://media.timeout.com/images/106138839/image.jpg]

【37†Leonie Cooper】 Food and Drink Editor, Time Out London

【58†Andy Parsons for Time Out】

【58†13. M Manze】

  * Restaurants 
  * Pie and mash shop 
  * Bermondsey 

Michele Manze and family arrived from Italy in 1878, started out as ice-cream merchants and finally opened this pie, mash and eel shop on Tower Bridge Road in 1902. Inside, little seems to have changed since those early days: the Victorian green-tiled interiors speak of history, while the pie and mash is reckoned to be some of the best in town. A truly iconic London feast and one that comes with a reasonable price to boot. 

Price: Pie and mash, £5.50.

(R) - ONLY trains designated with an R at the top of the column will operate when limited service conditions or special circumstances warrant. (R+) - Train will operate or add additional stops when the R+ schedule is operated, in addition to trains with an R at the top of the column.

(C) - Connecting bus operated by Eastern Panhandle Transit Authority (EPTA). You must have a MARC-issued ticket with a destination in West Virginia or purchase a MARC ticket from the ticket machine in the station at Brunswick to ride the bus. EPTA is responsible for this bus and operation is subject to continued funding from the State of West Virginia.

[Image 30: Bikes Allowed] All MARC trains provide accommodation for full-size, non-collapsible bikes. Look for illuminated green lights or a large green reflective decal with the bike symbol on the outside of the railcar and board at the adjacent door. (L) - Train may leave this stop 5 minutes early.

(d) - Train stops to discharge passengers only and may depart ahead of schedule. Passengers boarding at these stations should arrive at least 10 minutes early.

(R) - ONLY trains designated with an R at the top of the column will operate when limited service conditions or special circumstances warrant. On days of heavy snowfall or other severe weather, MARC will operate this special schedule. Additional stops marked with an R will be made when this schedule is in effect. See the 【73†PDF schedule】 for complete R schedule details.

(R+) - Train will operate or add additional stops when the R+ schedule is operated, in addition to trains with an R at the top of the column.

(C) - Connecting bus operated by Eastern Panhandle Transit Authority (EPTA). You must have a MARC-issued ticket with a destination in West Virginia or purchase a MARC ticket from the ticket machine in the station at Brunswick to ride the bus. EPTA is responsible for this bus and operation is subject to continued funding from the State of West Virginia.

[Image 30: Bikes Allowed] All MARC trains provide accommodation for full-size, non-collapsible bikes. Look for illuminated green lights or a large green reflective decal with the bike symbol on the outside of the railcar and board at the adjacent door. Method of securement for bicycles varies between railcar types; passengers must bring two (2) bungee cords to secure their bicycles. 【75†Click here for more details】.

(L) - Train may leave this stop 5 minutes early.

(d) - Train stops to discharge passengers only and may depart ahead of schedule. Passengers boarding at these stations should arrive at least 10 minutes early.

(R) - ONLY trains designated with an R at the top of the column will operate when limited service conditions or special circumstances warrant. On days of heavy snowfall or other severe weather, MARC will operate this special schedule. Additional stops marked with an R will be made when this schedule is in effect. See the 【73†PDF schedule】 for complete R schedule details.

(R+) - Train will operate or add additional stops when the R+ schedule is operated, in addition to trains with an R at the top of the column.

(C) - Connecting bus operated by Eastern Panhandle Transit Authority (EPTA). You must have a MARC-issued ticket with a destination in West Virginia or purchase a MARC ticket from the ticket machine in the station at Brunswick to ride the bus. EPTA is responsible for this bus and operation is subject to continued funding from the State of West Virginia.

[Image 30: Bikes Allowed] All MARC trains provide accommodation for full-size, non-collapsible bikes. Look for illuminated green lights or a large green reflective decal with the bike symbol on the outside of the railcar and board at the adjacent door. Method of securement for bicycles varies between railcar types; passengers must bring two (2) bungee cords to secure their bicycles. 【75†Click here for more details】.

(R+) - Train will operate or add additional stops when the R+ schedule is operated, in addition to trains with an R at the top of the column.

(C) - Connecting bus operated by Eastern Panhandle Transit Authority (EPTA). You must have a MARC-issued ticket with a destination in West Virginia or purchase a MARC ticket from the ticket machine in the station at Brunswick to ride the bus. EPTA is responsible for this bus and operation is subject to continued funding from the State of West Virginia.

[Image 30: Bikes Allowed] All MARC trains provide accommodation for full-size, non-collapsible bikes. Look for illuminated green lights or a large green reflective decal with the bike symbol on the outside of the railcar and board at the adjacent door. Method of securement for bicycles varies between railcar types; passengers must bring two (2) bungee cords to secure their bicycles. 【75†Click here for more details】.

(L) - Train may leave this stop 5 minutes early.

(d) - Train stops to discharge passengers only and may depart ahead of schedule. Passengers boarding at these stations should arrive at least 10 minutes early.

(R) - ONLY trains designated with an R at the top of the column will operate when limited service conditions or special circumstances warrant. On days of heavy snowfall or other severe weather, MARC will operate this special schedule. Additional stops marked with an R will be made when this schedule is in effect. See the 【73†PDF schedule】 for complete R schedule details.

(R+) - Train will operate or add additional stops when the R+ schedule is operated, in addition to trains with an R at the top of the column.

(C) - Connecting bus operated by Eastern Panhandle Transit Authority (EPTA). You must have a MARC-issued ticket with a destination in West Virginia or purchase a MARC ticket from the ticket machine in the station at Brunswick to ride the bus. EPTA is responsible for this bus and operation is subject to continued funding from the State of West Virginia.

[Image 30: Bikes Allowed] All MARC trains provide accommodation for full-size, non-collapsible bikes. Look for illuminated green lights or a large green reflective decal with the bike symbol on the outside of the railcar and board at the adjacent door. Method of securement for bicycles varies between railcar types; passengers must bring two (2) bungee cords to secure their bicycles. 【75†Click here for more details】.

(L) - Train may leave this stop 5 minutes early.

(d) - Train stops to discharge passengers only and may depart ahead of schedule. Passengers boarding at these stations should arrive at least 10 minutes early.

(R) - ONLY trains designated with an R at the top of the column will operate when limited service conditions or special circumstances warrant. On days of heavy snowfall or other severe weather, MARC will operate this special schedule. Additional stops marked with an R will be made when this schedule is in effect. See the 【73†PDF schedule】 for complete R schedule details.

(R+) - Train will operate or add additional stops when the R+ schedule is operated, in addition to trains with an R at the top of the column.

(C) - Connecting bus operated by Eastern Panhandle Transit Authority (EPTA). You must have a MARC-issued ticket with a destination in West Virginia or purchase a MARC ticket from the ticket machine in the station at Brunswick to ride the bus. EPTA is responsible for this bus and operation is subject to continued funding from the State of West Virginia.

[Image 30: Bikes Allowed] All MARC trains provide accommodation for full-size, non-collapsible bikes. Look for illuminated green lights or a large green reflective decal with the bike symbol on the outside of the railcar and board at the adjacent door. Method of securement for bicycles varies between railcar types; passengers must bring two (2) bungee cords to secure their bicycles. 【75†Click here for more details】.

(L) - Train may leave this stop 5 minutes early.

(d) - Train stops to discharge passengers only and may depart ahead of schedule. Passengers boarding at these stations should arrive at least 10 minutes early.

(R) - ONLY trains designated with an R at the top of the column will operate when limited service conditions or special circumstances warrant. On days of heavy snowfall or other severe weather, MARC will operate this special schedule. Additional stops marked with an R will be made when this schedule is in effect. See the 【73†PDF schedule】 for complete R schedule details.

(R+) - Train will operate or add additional stops when the R+ schedule is operated, in addition to trains with an R at the top of the column.

(C) - Connecting bus operated by Eastern Panhandle Transit Authority (EPTA). You must have a MARC-issued ticket with a destination in West Virginia or purchase a MARC ticket from the ticket machine in the station at Brunswick to ride the bus. EPTA is responsible for this bus and operation is subject to continued funding from the State of West Virginia.

[Image 30: Bikes Allowed] All MARC trains provide accommodation for full-size, non-collapsible bikes. Look for illuminated green lights or a large green reflective decal with the bike symbol on the outside of the railcar and board at the adjacent door. Method of securement for bicycles varies between railcar types; passengers must bring two (2) bungee cords to secure their bicycles. 【75†Click here for more details】.

## Customer Service Promise

The State of Maryland pledges to provide constituents, businesses, customers, and stakeholders with friendly and courteous, timely and responsive, accurate and consistent, accessible and convenient, and truthful and transparent services.

【110†Take Our Survey†www.maryland.gov】

## Help Stop Fraud in State Government

The Maryland General Assembly’s Office of Legislative Audits operates a toll-free fraud hotline to receive allegations of fraud and/or abuse of State government resources. Information reported to the hotline in the past has helped to eliminate certain fraudulent activities and protect State resources.
